Here's the approach:

### 1. Define theme resource dictionaries

Create three `ResourceDictionary` files (e.g., `LightTheme.xaml`, `DarkTheme.xaml`, `HighContrastTheme.xaml`) each defining the same keys with different values:

```xml
<!-- Themes/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

Repeat for `DarkTheme.xaml` and `HighContrastTheme.xaml` with appropriate colors.

### 2. Apply theme dynamically in `App.xaml.cs`

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public void ApplyTheme(string themeName)
    {
        ResourceDictionary theme = themeName switch
        {
            "Dark"         => new DarkTheme(),
            "HighContrast"  => new HighContrastTheme(),
            _               => new LightTheme(),
        };

        // Remove the old theme dictionary and add the new one
        Resources.MergedDictionaries.Clear();
        Resources.MergedDictionaries.Add(theme);
    }
}
```

### 3. Use `DynamicResource` in your XAML (not `StaticResource`)

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryText}" Text="Hello!" />
</ContentPage>
```

`DynamicResource` is key — it re-evaluates when the dictionary changes, giving you instant updates.

### 4. Settings page to switch themes

```csharp
public partial class SettingsPage : ContentPage
{
    void OnThemeSelected(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        string chosen = themePicker.SelectedItem as string; // "Light", "Dark", "HighContrast"
        ((App)Application.Current).ApplyTheme(chosen);

        // Persist the choice
        Preferences.Set("AppTheme", chosen);
    }
}
```

### 5. Restore on startup

In `App` constructor, after `InitializeComponent()`:

```csharp
ApplyTheme(Preferences.Get("AppTheme", "Light"));
```

**Key points:**
- Always use `DynamicResource`, never `StaticResource`, for themed values.
- `Preferences` (from `Microsoft.Maui.Storage`) persists the selection across launches.
- Keep all three dictionaries with identical keys so swapping is seamless.
